{{Infobox song | Type = [[Promotional recording|Promotional single]] | Name = Reach for the Stars (Mars Edition) | Cover = William-reachforthestars.png | Artist = [[will.i.am]] | Album = [[Willpower (will.i.am album)|#willpower]] | Released = {{start date|2012|08|28}} | Recorded = | Format = [[music download|Digital download]] | Genre = {{hlist|[[Orchestral music|Orchestral]]|[[ambient music|ambient]]}} | Length = 4:21 | Label = {{hlist|[[Will.i.am Music Group|will.i.am]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}} | Writer = {{hlist|William Adams|Kenny Oliver|Onlee Gill}} | Producer = {{hlist|will.i.am|[[Dr. Luke]]|Verrigni|}} | Misc = | prev = "Ghetto Ghetto" | prev_no = 15 | track_no = 16 | next = "Smile Mona Lisa" | next_no = 17 }}
"'''Reach for the Stars'''", alternately subtitled "'''Mars Edition'''" and "'''NASA Edition'''", is a song written, produced and recorded by American recording artist [[will.i.am]] in commemoration of the landing of the [[Curiosity (rover)|''Curiosity'' rover]] on the planet [[Mars]]. First released on August 28, 2012 as a promotional single, the song also appears on the deluxe edition of his fourth studio album ''[[willpower (will.i.am album)|#willpower]]'' (2013). "Reach for the Stars (Mars Edition)" became the first song in history to be broadcast from another planet, completing a journey of more than 300 million miles between Mars and Earth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/29/us/mars-single/index.html?hpt=hp_c2 |title=Will.i.am premieres song -- from Mars |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=January 25, 2014 |last=Karimi |first=Faith}}</ref>
== Background and development == "Reach for the Stars" was written in February 2011, after NASA asked will.i.am to write and produce a song for the Curiosity rover's landing on Mars. The songwriter said that the experience with NASA administrator Charles Bolden discussing the possibility of broadcasting a song from Mars was "surreal". The song is part of NASA's educational outreach, with will.i.am stating that the song "aims to encourage youth to study science". Rather than produce a song via the computer, will.i.am stated that he wanted to show "human collaboration", which featured a 40-piece orchestra. He added that "people in my field aren't supposed to try and execute something classical, or orchestral, so I wanted to break that stigma, [and have something] that would be timeless and translated in different cultures."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/william-to-debut-track-on-mars-using-speakers-of-the-curiosity-rover/story-e6frfn09-1226458672800 |title=Will.i.am track played on Mars using speakers from the Curiosity rover |work=news.com.au |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=August 30, 2012}}</ref>
NASA had confirmed during the [[Mars Science Laboratory]] launch tweet-up on November 24, 2011 that will.i.am had partnered with NASA to deliver a song for Curiosity's landing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://solotravelgirl.com/nasatweetup-rock-star-will-i-am-partners-with-nasa-has-a-s-y-s-t-e-m-to-make-science-and-technology-cool/|title=#NASATweetup: Rock Star Will 1x Partners with NASA, Has a S.Y.S.T.E.M. to Make Science and Technology Cool| work = Solo Travel Girl |date=27 November 2012 |accessdate= 17 November 2017}}</ref> After being uploaded to the rover, which landed near the equator of Mars, the song was broadcast live from the planet, completing a journey of more than 300 million miles (approximately 482 million kilometers).<ref name="HP">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/29/william-mars-reach-for-the-stars-curiosity_n_1838826.html|title=Will.i.am & Mars: 'Reach For The Stars' Beamed From Curiosity Rover|work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=August 29, 2012|accessdate=August 30, 2012}}</ref> It became the first song in history to be broadcast from another planet and the second song to be broadcast in space, after [[the Beatles]]' "[[Across the Universe]]" was beamed into space by NASA in 2008.<ref name="HP"/>
